04320nam a22006615i 9781477313978DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212017txu    fo  d z      eng d  a2016058736  a97814773139787 a10.7560/7594802doi  a(DE-B1597)587553  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX00aHV7936.D78bH63 2017 7aSOC0040002bisacsh04a362.2992231 aHoberman, John, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDopers in Uniform :bThe Hidden World of Police on Steroids /cJohn Hoberman. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2017  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One: What We Know about Cops on Steroids -- tChapter Two: Police Chiefs and the Steroid Dilemma -- tChapter Three: Police Unions and Steroids -- tChapter Four: The Gym Culture, Where Muscular Cops Meet -- tChapter Five: Steroids in the Military -- tConclusion -- tAcknowledgments -- tAppendix: An Iraq War Army Veteran on Steroid Use in Combat, by Shawn Fogarty -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe recorded use of deadly force against unarmed suspects and sustained protest from the Black Lives Matter movement, among others, have ignited a national debate about excessive violence in American policing. Missing from the debate, however, is any discussion of a factor that is almost certainly contributing to the violence—the use of anabolic steroids by police officers. Mounting evidence from a wide range of credible sources suggests that many cops are abusing testosterone and its synthetic derivatives. This drug use is illegal and encourages a “steroidal” policing style based on aggressive behaviors and hulking physiques that diminishes public trust in law enforcement. Dopers in Uniform offers the first assessment of the dimensions and consequences of the felony use of anabolic steroids in major urban police departments. Marshalling an array of evidence, John Hoberman refutes the frequent claim that police steroid use is limited to a few “bad apples,” explains how the “Blue Wall of Silence” stymies the collection of data, and introduces readers to the broader marketplace for androgenic drugs. He then turns his attention to the people and organizations at the heart of police culture: the police chiefs who often see scandals involving steroid use as a distraction from dealing with more dramatic forms of misconduct and the police unions that fight against steroid testing by claiming an officer’s “right to privacy” is of greater importance. Hoberman’s findings clearly demonstrate the crucial need to analyze and expose the police steroid culture for the purpose of formulating a public policy to deal with its dysfunctional effects.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aPolicexDrug testingzUnited States. 0aPolicexDrug usezUnited States. 0aPolice--Drug use--United States. 0aSteroid abuse. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/75948040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477313978423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477313978/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK